ce:section.ce:para:
Progesterone, as a precursor of many steroidal hormones, is associated with the stabilization and control of hormonal levels in the reproductive cycle [1]. An imbalance of P4 levels in mammals can lead to malformation of the reproductive system, including delayed conception, high proportion of miscarriage and, in severe cases, infertility [
                        3
                     ]. For economic animal husbandry, a clear understanding of progesterone levels during the pre-pregnancy and pregnancy can considerably upsurge the chances of conception and calving, and the economic income as well [
                        4
                     ]. Traditional quantitative methods such as high performance liquid chromatography (HPLC), liquid chromatography–mass spectrometry assay (LC–MS), thin layer chromatography (TLC), and chemiluminescence enzyme immunoassay (CLEIA) [5] are widely applied for detection of P4 concentrations. Despite these traditional techniques have obvious advantages (HPLC – high separation efficiency with good selectivity, LC-MS – good analysis range, TLC – simple device and operates on square wave method, and CLEIA – good stability, low reagents toxicity and no radiological hazard), they typically require more detailed characterization, sample pretreatment, which increases the measurement time, specialized laboratories and expertise, which are time consuming, more expensive and are not appropriate for on-site analysis, and special experimental conditions [6,7]. Molecular imprinting technology (MIT) has also shown its application possibility in P4 determination [8,9], but at the same time, incomplete template removal and recombination kinetics of imprinted molecules hindered its real- time application [10]. Generally, the detection range and limit of the some sensors for directly reducing or oxidizing P4 are inconsistent with the P4 content in actual samples such as milk and serum, most likely due to the non-optimistic long-term stability of the sensor, which makes it difficult to provide a commercial product [11]. Therefore, low-cost, simple pretreatment, environmentally friendly, high selectivity and sensitivity electrochemical sensors have attracted more attentions recently [12].
